In proportion as this visit to Rome shews, as a pro· bable result, the elevation of henaeus to the vacant see, the prosecution of his journey to the far distant East, as stated by Feuardentius and Le Sueur, becomes in the same degree improbable. Neither is it at all likely, that he should have been the author of the account of the per· secution sent from Lyons to the Churches of Asia, if he had not been an eye-witness.
